18 Appium Caecum: Appius Claudius Caecus, oens. 312-308 Β. c. cons. 307 and 296, statesman, poet and orator, the builder of the earliest aqueduct and the Appian way. Roman literature, jurisprudence and grammar (R litteram invenit ut pro Valesiis Valerii essent,’ cp. Teuffel, ἓ 90, 2) may be said to begin with him. His famous speech against Pyrrhus (B. c. 280) was long extant and constituted the earliest specimen of literary Latin prose. The present comparison with Cato was perhaps suggested by Cic. Brut. 16, 61 cited c. 18 8.

XII 10,12 ff. seems to show that many of the oppnobrious epithets here accumulated actually occurred in the very correspondence, expressly cited imme- diately below, both Tacitus and Quintilian having probably taken them at second hand from Mucianus' ‘Epistolae.'
